record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1660,
  "cap": "CRED_EXPOSURE",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/events (WS handshake forces query-token branch)",
  "rationale": "The /api/v1/events endpoint is structurally locked into the query-token auth branch because browsers cannot set the Authorization header on a WebSocket upgrade — the WebSocket constructor exposes no header API. Any UI or third-party client that opens this stream from a browser MUST embed the bearer in `?token=<bearer>` (router.rs:141), guaranteeing the secret hits TraceLayer's URI logging on every WS handshake. Unlike fetch() callers who can choose Authorization-header auth, WS clients have no opt-out. Compounded with finding #1 (no Origin check) this means: every UI session writes the bearer to logs, and any cross-origin page can replay it. Static pass missed this composition because it requires recognising both the WS browser-API constraint and the logging surface together.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "open the operator UI, then `journalctl -u nyctos | grep -oE 'token=[A-Za-z0-9_-]+' | head` — first hit is the live bearer."
}

