record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 928,
  "cap": "PATH_TRAVERSAL",
  "endpoint": "DELETE /api/v1/projects/:project_id/repos/:name",
  "rationale": "delete_project_repo computes target = s.state_repos_dir.join(&name) and immediately std::fs::remove_dir_all(&target) (router.rs:927-931). The repo name is operator-supplied via CreateRepoRequest::name and only validated for `trim().is_empty()` at :728 — no rejection of `..`, path separators, NUL bytes, or absolute paths. Path::join on Unix replaces the base when the second component is absolute, so name=`/etc/some-attacker-chosen-dir` resolves outside state_repos_dir; name=`..` walks one level up; name=`../../..` reaches the filesystem root region. The DB-side `repos.name` column has no path-shape constraint either (nyctos-core/store/repos.rs), so a hostile name persists through upsert and survives until DELETE. The route uses :name as a single path segment, but `%2e%2e` URL-decodes back to `..` and curl --path-as-is delivers it intact. Net: authenticated arbitrary-directory deletion under the daemon's UID, including the daemon's own state_dir / nyctos.toml on a second pass. Static pass missed because the source (POST handler) and sink (DELETE handler) are split across two functions with the DB row as the laundering step — taint flow doesn't reconnect across the persistence boundary.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "POST /api/v1/projects/proj-x/repos {\"name\":\"..\",\"source_kind\":\"local-path\",\"source_url_or_path\":\"/tmp\",\"i_own_this\":true} then DELETE /api/v1/projects/proj-x/repos/%2e%2e — observe state_repos_dir's parent vanish."
}

