record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-core/src/repo/git.rs",
  "line": 89,
  "cap": "CRED_EXPOSURE",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/projects/:project_id/repos (auth_ref=\"token-env:<ARBITRARY_VAR>\") then any /api/v1/runs that triggers ingest_git",
  "rationale": "ingest_git resolves token-env auth by calling `std::env::var(var)` with the operator-supplied `var` name and immediately POSTs the resulting secret to api.github.com via `validate_token_scopes` → `reqwest.get(GITHUB_USER_PROBE_URL).bearer_auth(token)` (git.rs:86-99, :476-498). `GitAuth::parse` (repo/mod.rs:93-98) rejects only an empty value; any other string is accepted as a var name. session-0014's `validate_git_auth_ref` (router.rs:864-885) does not constrain var-name shape either. Two primitives: (a) **forced cross-tenant exfiltration** — an authenticated attacker sets `auth_ref=\"token-env:AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY\"` (or `DATABASE_URL`, `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY`, `OPENAI_API_KEY`, anything else the operator exported into the daemon's env), and every ingest transmits that secret as a Bearer credential to api.github.com, depositing it in GitHub's request logs and in any TLS-MITM position the daemon's host trusts (corporate proxy, hostile root CA). The same value is also briefly written into the child git process env as `GIT_CONFIG_VALUE_1=Authorization: Bearer <secret>` (git.rs:250) for the duration of `git clone`, exposing it via `/proc/<pid>/environ` to any same-uid local reader. (b) **env-var existence + setness oracle** — the three error variants surfaced through AgentEvent are observable: `AuthEnvMissing` (var unset), `AuthScopeStatus { status: 401 }` (var set; value not a GitHub token — i.e. value *did* exfiltrate), `AuthTokenWriteScope` (var set and GitHub recognised the value as a write-scope PAT — confirms the secret is in fact a GH PAT). An authenticated attacker can enumerate the daemon's environment by walking var names; the response disambiguates 'unset' from 'set-and-leaked'. Distinct from findings #4 / #5 (which leak the *nyctos* bearer via query-string logging) — this finding exfiltrates *third-party* secrets out of the daemon's env to GitHub. Static pass missed it because the source (`auth_ref` JSON field) and the network sink (outbound bearer_auth) sit in different crates with the DB row + ingest pass as the laundering steps; the validator added in session-0014 looked sufficient against the AuthMalformed shape but did not constrain the var-name semantically.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "POST /api/v1/projects/proj-x/repos {\"name\":\"probe\",\"source_kind\":\"github\",\"source_url_or_path\":\"https://github.com/torvalds/linux.git\",\"auth_ref\":\"token-env:AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY\",\"i_own_this\":true}; POST /api/v1/runs to trigger ingest; observe events bus for `AuthScopeStatus { status: 401 }` (var present, value already exfiltrated to GitHub) vs `AuthEnvMissing` (var absent). Mitigate by allowlisting var-name shapes (e.g. `^NYCTOS_GIT_TOKEN_[A-Z0-9_]+$`) and never sending arbitrary env contents to an external scope-probe endpoint — gate the GitHub scope probe behind a host-allowlist check on the repo URL first."
}

