  "endpoint": "POST /webhook/git (pre-auth)",
  "rationale": "is_always_open (router.rs:122-126) exempts /webhook/git from bearer auth on the rationale that 'HMAC IS the auth'. But the route is registered unconditionally at :88, and webhook_git (webhook.rs:421-444) returns three structurally distinct status codes BEFORE any HMAC check runs: 500 ApiError::Internal('webhook not enabled') when state.webhook is None (operator never set [triggers].webhook_secret_ref); 503 WebhookResponse('webhook secret is not configured') when state.webhook is Some but the env-backed secret resolves to None (env var unset, empty, or literal-empty — see EnvSecretResolver:207-222); 401 Unauthorized when state.webhook is Some, secret resolves, and the X-Hub-Signature-256 header is missing or malformed. An unauthenticated remote attacker probing /webhook/git with no body distinguishes (a) webhook entirely disabled, (b) webhook configured-but-broken-secret, (c) webhook armed — a 3-way reconnaissance oracle obtained pre-auth. Stage (b) is especially actionable: it confirms the operator *intended* webhook authentication but operationally broke it, signalling a window where retrying with empty HMAC repeatedly (each attempt logged by TraceLayer at :89) generates noise indistinguishable from real failed deliveries, plausibly masking subsequent exploitation. Distinct from existing findings — those concern bearer-gated routes; this is a pre-auth status-code oracle. Mitigation: register /webhook/git conditionally (only when state.webhook.is_some()), collapse the three states to a single uniform 401 with no body, or move the route under a path that is 404 when state.webhook is None.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "curl -i -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8088/webhook/git -H 'X-Hub-Signature-256: sha256=00...00' (64 zeros) — observe 500 vs 503 vs 401 to fingerprint operator webhook posture without ever holding the bearer."
}

